body:
Hi @jjcao,

It might be related to a pytorch version issue as AFAIK, building extensions was done differently before pytorch v4. I have tested ```python setup.py install" on pytorchv4 and pytorchv1
My current setup is : 

CUDA 10
Pytorch v1
python 3.7
gcc g++ 7.3

Can you try different gcc version ? gcc5 or 4.7 ? if you want to try gcc7, you'll need cuda10 most likely.

Best,
Thibault

Also I am currently doing a major upgrade of the code to make things a bit smoother. Please git pull frequently to make sure you have the latest version of the code.  I might introduce some additional typos in the process, so it would be a huge help if you report the error you face during the setup.

Thank you. 
cuda 9 + python: 3.7 + gcc 5 => success

Hi @ThibaultGROUEIX 
I pulled the latest code and running the same as you, cuda10, pytorch 1.0, python 3.7, gcc 7.3.
When I execute `python setup.py install` I get the error

`cc1plus: error: /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcudnn.so.5/include: Not a directory`

Alongside that it also prints out the gcc command with the include option `-I/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcudnn.so.5/include`. If I change that to 

`-I/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcudnn.so.5`

and rerun the gcc command, it executes without any errors. 
Do you know where I can change this to make the whole installation work with `python setup.py install`?

I don't have cudnn installed : i don't have the folder ```/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcudnn.so.5```
Maybe just try removing it ? (it could be a mismatch between cudnn version and cuda version maybe).

Hi @awaelchli , 

It's very likely that this error happens because you either set the environment variable 'CUDNN_HOME' or 'CUDNN_PATH'.

From there, 2 possibilites.

- You can remove the env variables, but it is likely that you use it for other projects.

- Otherwise, you can try to add the following lines at the beginning of your setup.py in order to delete the env variables only in the child process : 

`import os`
`if 'CUDNN_HOME' in os.environ: del os.environ['CUDNN_HOME']`
`if 'CUDNN_PATH' in os.environ: del os.environ['CUDNN_PATH']`

Hope it helps,
Pierre-Alain

Thanks @ThibaultGROUEIX 
After I uninstalled/removed the cudnn, it compiled. However when I import the chamfer module I get

`>>> import chamfer`
`Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: /home/adrian/research/envs/research/lib/python3.7/site-packages/chamfer-0.0.0-py3.7-linux-x86_64.egg/chamfer.cpython-37m-x86_64-linux-gnu.so: undefined symbol: _ZN2at19UndefinedTensorImpl10_singletonE`

which I have seen in the past when the wrong GCC version was used for compiling. But I double checked it is using GCC 7.3. I also tried gcc 5.
great news ! from https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/cppextension-loading-complains-undefined-symbol/27908/4 , try to ```import torch``` first

@ThibaultGROUEIX Oh, wow. Yep that did the trick. That's funny. Thanks!!!
@palanglois  I only saw your answer just now. Indeed I had the CUDNN_HOME variable defined, I think for tensorflow. Now with your post I can leave it there, thanks!
